                     <interp inst="t17860111-2-person179" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , for he had none of him before, nor of Mr. Sawtell; but as I have told you, his story goes on to say, that about the latter end of November, and in this he will be confirmed by his wife, who was present at several of the transactions and her maid; that towards the end of November or beginning of December 1782, 
               <persName id="t17860111-2-person180">
                  Nathaniel
                   Goodridge
               <interp inst="t17860111-2-person180" type="surname" value="Goodridge"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17860111-2-person180" type="given" value="Nathaniel"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17860111-2-person180" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             had frequently been applying to him about getting a will from Mr. Sawtell (all that I say now, you will take to be his story) it was intended that Underwood should draw this will, sometime past, he found his total inability to draw a will for a man whose circumstances he knew nothing of, and whose fortune, where it lay, or what it consisted of he was a stranger to, he therefore said it was not possible for him to do it: then the scheme was formed of getting at his will; it was known perfectly that he had made a will, and it was supposed, and perhaps known, that that will was in favour of Mr. 
               <persName id="t17860111-2-person181">
                  Thomas
                   Slack
               <interp inst="t17860111-2-person181" type="surname" value="Slack"></interp>
